# i-am-the-CA-now

> CVE-2026-26151 made RDP annoying again, but you know who you can trust. *use with caution.*

the dialog wanted to know who signed this .rdp file. the dialog now knows.

## the deal

microsoft shipped a security update in april 2026 that makes you click through a yellow consent dialog every time you open a .rdp file. publisher: unknown. redirections all off by default. fine if you're a target of nation-state phishing, kind of fucking annoying if you're just trying to log into your hosted environment for the 400th time this month.

the fix microsoft wants you to do: get a code-signing cert from your enterprise PKI, sign your .rdp files, push the thumbprint via GPO.

cool. great. love that for them.

the fix for the rest of us: become your own PKI. it's one machine. who's gonna stop you.

## what it does

- generates a self-signed code-signing cert; `CN=RDP-Signing-<hostname>`, lives in the local machine store
- imports it into `LocalMachine\Root` so the chain validates
- imports it into `LocalMachine\TrustedPublisher` so authenticode trusts signatures from it
- enables the `AllowSignedFiles` policy and adds the thumbprint to `TrustedCertThumbprints`
- sets `RdpLaunchConsentAccepted` so the educational first-launch dialog doesn't ambush you
- signs every .rdp on your desktop with `rdpsign.exe /sha256`
- idempotent; safe to re-run when mstsc inevitably overwrites a signature

you are now a root CA on this machine. that's the trade.

if that sentence makes you uncomfortable, it should. the lower-power option is the registry revert at the bottom of [microsoft's own doc](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-desktop-services/remotepc/understanding-security-warnings); flip `RedirectionWarningDialogVersion` to `1` and you get the pre-april behavior back, no cert shenanigans. microsoft has also said they might yank that switch in a future update, so... pick your poison.

## usage

right-click → run with powershell. or:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\Sign-MyRDPs.ps1
```

it'll UAC-prompt itself if you forgot to elevate.

## when it stops working

mstsc rewrites .rdp files when you connect; that invalidates the signature. if the yellow dialog comes back, just re-run the script. takes two seconds. or rename your .rdp to something other than `Default.rdp` and mark it read-only:

```powershell
Set-ItemProperty .\myconnection.rdp -Name IsReadOnly -Value $true
```

mstsc will complain it can't save settings. that's the point.

## things this is not

- not a substitute for actual enterprise PKI; if you have ADCS, use that instead
- not portable across machines; each box generates its own cert under its own hostname (this is on purpose; the private key stays local)
- not signed itself; if your execution policy is set to restricted you'll need `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass` or to sign it yourself (...with the cert you just made, if you wanna get cute about it)
- not endorsed by anyone; especially not microsoft, who would prefer you stand up a CA

## the real fix

if you're getting these .rdp files from a vendor (your hosted desktop provider, your MSP, whoever); ask them to sign their .rdp files. they probably can. they just don't by default because their support tickets haven't caught up to april 14th yet.

until then: i-am-the-CA-now.
